hilosophical theories. The significance of art’s realism in times characterised by the normalisation of fake, manipulated and distorted representations of reality can only be fully understood by attending to the ways that the arts mediate, visualise and even shape reality. Each chapter features a different approach to realism and its aesthetic dimensions not only in the visual arts, but also in sound art, film, scientific imaging and literature.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aArtxPolitical aspects. 0aRealism in art. 0aTruthfulness and falsehood. 4aPhilosophy. 7aART / Criticism.2bisacsh1 aBoetzkes, Amanda , eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBoetzkes, Amanda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOuellet, Maryse, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOuellet, Maryse, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311079765740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978139952413140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781399524131423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781399524131/original  a978-3-11-079765-7  Edinburgh University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles